{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503149"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:55:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:55:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1935"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1935"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.1,0.63,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1935"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31412"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1935"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1935"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17219"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"281"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"667"},{"type":"contributions","id":"697"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1022"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42426"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31412"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman is being assessed for her ongoing management of Graves\u0027 disease. She developed Graves\u0027 disease six months ago and was treated with carbimazole. However, the treatment proved to be ineffective and she remains biochemically hyperthyroid on her recent thyroid function test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her exophthalmos has progressed since the last visit. She developed bilateral lid retraction a week ago and now complains of double vision. She expresses concern that her exophthalmos is getting more severe and she feels embarrassed to go out in public.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no other medical co-morbidities and does not take any other medication apart from carbimazole.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Radioactive iodine","Propylthiouracil","Thyroidectomy","Propranolol","Iodine supplement"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with Graves\u0027 disease that proves to be ineffective to antithyroid drugs. In addition, the Graves\u0027 ophthalmopathy seems to be worsening with severe exophthalmos, new onset of diplopia and lid retraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most definitive treatment in Graves\u0027 disease, in this case, is \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E.\u0026nbsp; This patient is a young woman who has no co-morbidities and would be a fit candidate for surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERadioactive iodine is also another definitive treatment of Graves\u0027 disease. This treatment is useful for patients with high surgical risk or previous surgery irradiation of the neck. However, radioactive iodine may initially worsen the appearance and symptoms of her Graves\u0027 ophthalmopathy. Hence, radioactive iodine is contraindicated in patients with severe graves ophthalmopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer antithyroid drug (carbimazole) has failed to achieve euthyroidism in this individual\u2019s Graves\u0027 disease. Switching one antithyroid drug to another (propylthiouracil) will most likely achieve similar ineffective results.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBeta-blockers only provide symptomatic relief for Graves\u0027 disease and is not a definitive treatment.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIodine supplements are used in hypothyroidism instead.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Thyroidectomy is the preferred treatment option for Graves\u0027 disease complicated by exophthalmos."],"references":["Sridama V, DeGroot LJ. Treatment of Graves\u0027 disease and the course of ophthalmopathy. Am J Med 1989; 87:70.","Salvi M, Campi I. Medical Treatment of Graves\u0027 Orbitopathy. Horm Metab Res 2015; 47:779.","Kurihara H. Total thyroidectomy for the treatment of hyperthyroidism in patients with ophthalmopathy. Thyroid 2002; 12:265.","Laurberg P, Wallin G, Tallstedt L, et al. TSH-receptor autoimmunity in Graves\u0027 disease after therapy with anti-thyroid drugs, surgery, or radioiodine: a 5-year prospective randomized study. Eur J Endocrinol 2008; 158:69."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17219"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1935"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17219"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-01-08T15:41:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-01-08T15:41:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1935"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31412"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relations